Two things here:

My impression is that we use the builder annotations to report input data problems - an InterruptException is a programming error - or am I mistaken? It is not important to me what we land on, but it should be used consistent.
When catching InterruptException you should reset the Thread.currentThread().interrupt();, and if it is not deliberate I would exit like this:

try {
  Thread.sleep(100);
} catch (InterruptedException ex) {
  Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
  throw new RuntimeException(ex);
}

See: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4906799/why-invoke-thread-currentthread-interrupt-in-a-catch-interruptexception-block

